title: Licensing Appeals Board Rules Come into Operation Today
question_text: The following is issued on behalf of the Licensing Appeals Board The Licensing Appeals Board (LIAB) Rules made under section 125G of the Public Health and Municipal Services Ordinance (Chapter 132) come into operation today (March 15)
reply_text: The LIAB is a statutory body established under section 125A of the Ordinance to hear and determine any licensing appeals lodged under section 125 of the Ordinance.  To facilitate the discharge of its statutory responsibility, the LIAB has made the Rules to regulate the making of appeals to the LIAB, specify the documents to be lodged or served in relation to an appeal and provide for the hearing and determining of those appeals. Under section 125 of the Ordinance, a person dissatisfied with a decision made by the licensing authority to cancel or suspend any registration, licence or permit or to refuse any application for the grant or renewal thereof

cancel or suspend any registration, licence or permit or to refuse any application for the grant or renewal thereof may, within 14 days after the service on him of the notice of decision, appeal to the Licensing Appeals Board against the decision.   The new appeal mechanism is an improvement over the previous review mechanism, under which an application for review against the decision was required to be launched with the licensing authority. Under the new appeal mechanism, a person having a right of appeal shall commence an appeal by lodging a notice of appeal with the secretary of the LIAB direct.  The licensing authority will be required to provide with the Board a statement setting

the LIAB direct. The licensing authority will be required to provide with the Board a statement setting out, amongst others, the reasons for its decision and the relevant policy and with a copy of any document relevant to the appeal. The Board will hold hearings on the appeals and may affirm, vary or substitute its own decisions. March 15, 2000
